<BaseLayout title="About" description="Why SWE for Vibe Coders exists and who it's for.">
  <section class="container prose py-12">
    <h1 class="text-[2.4rem]">About this course</h1>
    <p class="text-[1.2rem] text-muted">
      AI coding tools made it possible to build real, working software without ever
      learning the craft underneath it. That’s genuinely great. But there’s a gap:
      the tools happily write code for you and quietly assume you know what a commit
      is, why tests exist, or that committing your API key is a bad day waiting to happen.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>SWE for Vibe Coders</strong> fills that gap. It teaches the small set of
      software-engineering fundamentals that stop you from losing work, breaking things
      in production, or getting stuck the moment the AI’s suggestion doesn’t work. No
      computer-science degree, no gatekeeping — just the practical stuff, taught the way
      you actually learn: by doing.
    </p>

    <h2>How it works</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Short lessons.</strong> Each one covers a single idea in a few minutes.</li>
      <li><strong>Check-yourself questions.</strong> Quick interactive prompts so you know an idea landed before you move on.</li>
      <li><strong>Real practice.</strong> Modules end with a hands-on exercise in an actual repo — because reading about git isn’t the same as using it.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Who it’s for</h2>
    <p>
      Anyone who can already make things with AI and wants to level up the engineering
      around it — indie hackers, designers-turned-builders, founders, and honestly the
      author of this course too. If you’ve ever thought “I probably should understand
      what this command does,” you’re in the right place.
    </p>

    <h2>Open source</h2>
    <p>
      The whole course is open source. Spot a mistake, or want to add a lesson?
      <a href="https://github.com/markoinla/swe-for-vibe-coders" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Contributions are welcome on GitHub.</a>
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
